---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="How to Read Your Salary Slip - Complete Indian Payslip Guide | PaySlipGen"
  description="Step-by-step guide to reading and understanding an Indian salary slip. Learn what each section means, how deductions work, and how to calculate your take-home pay."
  schema={{
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "How to Read Your Salary Slip",
    "description": "Complete guide to understanding every section of your Indian salary slip.",
    "author": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "PaySlipGen.in" },
    "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "PaySlipGen.in" },
    "datePublished": "2026-05-30",
    "dateModified": "2026-05-30",
    "mainEntityOfPage": { "@type": "WebPage", "@id": "https://payslipgen.in/how-to-read-salary-slip" }
  }}
>
  <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
      <a href="/" class="hover:text-indigo-600">Home</a>
      <span class="mx-2">/</span>
      <span class="text-gray-600">How to Read Salary Slip</span>
    </nav>

    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">How to Read Your Salary Slip</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-500 text-lg mb-8">A complete guide to understanding every section of your Indian payslip</p>

    <div class="prose prose-gray max-w-none space-y-8">
      <section>
        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">1. Header Section</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          The top of your salary slip contains the company name, logo, and address. It also shows the pay period (month and year) and the payment date. This section confirms which entity is paying you and for which period.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">2. Employee Details</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          This section lists your personal and employment information: name, employee ID, designation, department, date of joining, PAN number, PF account number, and bank details. Verify these are correct, especially your PAN and bank account number, as errors can affect tax filing and salary credit.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">3. Earnings (Additions)</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          The earnings section shows all components that add to your gross salary. Common line items include:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-600 mt-2 space-y-1">
          <li><strong>Basic Salary</strong> - Your core fixed pay</li>
          <li><strong>HRA</strong> - House rent allowance</li>
          <li><strong>Conveyance Allowance</strong> - Travel allowance (₹1,600 standard)</li>
          <li><strong>Medical Allowance</strong> - Health allowance (₹1,250 standard)</li>
          <li><strong>Special Allowance</strong> - Variable/flexible component</li>
          <li><strong>Other allowances</strong> - Leave travel, telephone, etc. (if applicable)</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mt-2">
          The sum of all these is your <strong>Gross Earnings</strong>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">4. Deductions</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          Deductions are amounts subtracted from your gross salary. These include:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-600 mt-2 space-y-1">
          <li><strong>PF (Employee contribution)</strong> - 12% of basic (capped at ₹15,000 basic)</li>
          <li><strong>ESI</strong> - 0.75% of gross (only if gross is ₹21,000 or below)</li>
          <li><strong>Professional Tax</strong> - State-level tax (₹200/month in most states)</li>
          <li><strong>TDS</strong> - Income tax deducted based on your declarations</li>
          <li><strong>Loan EMI deductions</strong> - If you have a salary advance or loan</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mt-2">
          The sum of all deductions is your <strong>Total Deductions</strong>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">5. Net Pay</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          <strong>Net Salary = Gross Earnings - Total Deductions</strong>
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mt-2">
          This is your take-home pay - the amount actually credited to your bank account. The slip often shows this in words as well, for verification purposes.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">6. CTC Breakdown</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          Some slips include a CTC (Cost to Company) breakdown showing the employer's contributions: employer PF contribution, gratuity accrual, and insurance premiums. These are costs borne by the company on your behalf and are not part of your take-home pay.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">7. Working Days vs Paid Days</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          Working days is the total number of days in the pay period. Paid days is the number of days you actually worked (excluding leave without pay). If paid days are less than working days, your earnings are pro-rated proportionally. For example, if you took 2 LOP days in a 30-day month, you get 28/30 of your earnings.
        </p>
      </section>

      <div class="bg-indigo-50 border border-indigo-200 rounded-xl p-6 mt-8">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-indigo-800 mb-2">Try Our Salary Slip Generator</h3>
        <p class="text-indigo-700 text-sm mb-3">See exactly how your salary breaks down with our free tool. Auto-calculates all components.</p>
        <a href="/generator" class="inline-block bg-indigo-600 hover:bg-indigo-700 text-white font-semibold px-6 py-2 rounded-lg transition-colors text-sm">
          Generate Your Slip &rarr;
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>
